msgid ""
"```shell\n"
"(.venv) ferris@rustbox [~/src/rust/guessing-game] % python\n"
"Python 3.9.6 (default, Aug 25 2021, 16:04:27)\n"
"[Clang 12.0.5 (clang-1205.0.22.9)] on darwin\n"
"Type \"help\", \"copyright\", \"credits\" or \"license\" for more "
"information.\n"
">>> import guessing_game\n"
">>> guessing_game.guess_the_number()\n"
"Guess the number!\n"
"Please input your guess.\n"
"42\n"
"You guessed: 42\n"
"Too small!\n"
"Please input your guess.\n"
"80\n"
"You guessed: 80\n"
"Too big!\n"
"Please input your guess.\n"
"50\n"
"You guessed: 50\n"
"Too small!\n"
"Please input your guess.\n"
"60\n"
"You guessed: 60\n"
"Too big!\n"
"Please input your guess.\n"
"55\n"
"You guessed: 55\n"
"You win!\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/tutorial.md:266
msgid "Create a wheel for distribution"
msgstr ""

#: src/tutorial.md:268
msgid ""
"`maturin develop` actually skips the wheel generation part and installs "
"directly in the current environment. `maturin build` on the other hand will "
"produce a wheel you can distribute. Note the wheel contains \"tags\" in its "
"filename that correspond to supported Python versions, platforms, and/or "
"architectures, so yours might look a little different. If you want to "
"distribute broadly, you may need to build on multiple platforms and use a "
"[`manylinux`](https://github.com/pypa/manylinux) Docker container to build "
"wheels compatible with a wide range of Linux distros."
msgstr ""

#: src/tutorial.md:285
msgid ""
"maturin can even publish wheels directly to [PyPI](https://pypi.org) with "
"`maturin publish`!"
msgstr ""

#: src/tutorial.md:288
msgid "Summary"
msgstr ""

#: src/tutorial.md:289
msgid ""
"Congratulations! You successfully created a Python module implemented "
"entirely in Rust thanks to pyo3 and maturin."
msgstr ""

#: src/tutorial.md:292
msgid ""
"This demonstrates how easy it is to get started with maturin, but keep "
"reading to learn more about all the additional features."
msgstr ""
